General information refers to the basic details about a product that would identify and describe it without getting into the detailed technical specifications.
A unique identifier assigned to a product by its manufacturer for inventory control and ordering purposes.
A unique identifier assigned to a specific product or component by the manufacturer.
The position where the product can be mounted
A classification of the product that indicates it meets certain industry or regulatory requirements.

A technical property generally refers to a characteristic or attribute that defines or describes the technical aspects of an object, system, material, or process. These properties are usually measurable or quantifiable and are critical in determining how something will function or perform in a specific context.
The inner diameter of the Laval nozzle, which is a part of the vacuum generator that accelerates the gas flow to create a vacuum.
The size of the holes in the grid of the vacuum generator.
The design of the silencer, which is the part of the vacuum generator that reduces noise.
A property that describes the type of vacuum generated by the ejector.
The size of the smallest particles that the vacuum generator can filter out.
A feature that allows the user to manually override the system's default settings.
The function that is integrated into the system to perform a specific task, in this case, generating an electric ejector pulse.
A data property that measures the amount of fluid or gas that flows through a system or component, often controlled or regulated by a valve or sensor.
A type of valve that is controlled by an electric signal and can open or close to allow or prevent the flow of fluid through it.
A component that separates solid particles from a fluid by means of a porous substance (sieve, screen, membrane, etc.)
The function of the switching element in the vacuum generator, which is a contact that does not conduct electricity when the switch is open.
A contact that can be switched between normally closed (N/C) and normally open (N/O) states.
The ability of a device to change its state or behavior in response to a specific input or condition.
